    "Firstly, by the joint continuity property of determinants (Lemma 2.7), it is sufficient to prove the statement for maps π and κ which are defined and smooth on R d. Since determinant is a multilinear map, we have the formuladet D(π 1,..., π d) -det D(κ 1,..., κ d) = det D(π 1 -κ 1, π 2,..., π d) + det D(κ 1, π 2 -κ 2, π 3,..., π d) + • • • + det D(κ 1,..., κ i-1, π i -κ i, π i+1,..., π d) + • • • + det D(κ 1,..., κ d-1, π d -κ d).Since determinant is also anti-symmetric, the above formula implies that alsodet D(π 1,..., π d) -det D(κ 1,..., κ d) = det D(π 1 -κ 1, π 2,..., π d) -det D(π 2 -κ 2, κ 1, π 3,..., π d) + • • • + (-1) i-1 det D(π i -κ i, κ 1,..., κ i-1, π i+1,..., π d) + • • • + (-1) d-1 det D(π d -κ d, κ 1,..., κ d-1).Therefore, using the Stokes theorem (2.4) for each of the summands yieldsQ det Dπ - Q det Dκ = d i=1 ∂Q (π i -κ i)⟨ω i (κ, π), Tan ∂Q ⟩dσ,whereω i (κ, π) = (-1) i-1 dκ 1 ∧ • • • ∧ dκ i-1 ∧ dπ i+1 ∧ • • • ∧ dπ d.In particular, by triangle inequality,| Q det Dπ - Q det Dκ | ≤ i | ∂Q (π i -κ i)⟨ω i (κ, π), Tan ∂Q ⟩dσ| (5.2)For each i ∈ {1,..., d}, by (2.3), we have|⟨ω i (κ, π), Tan ∂Q ⟩| ≤ L d-1, so that (5.2) implies | Q det Dπ - Q det Dκ| ≤ i ∥π i -κ i ∥ ℓ ∞ (∂Q) L d-1 σ(∂Q).Let us denote by F (d) the number of faces a d-dimensional cube has.",
    "Thenσ(Q) = r d-1 F(d) so that in particular | Q det Dπ - Q det Dκ| ≤ dF (d)r d-1 L d-1 ∥π -κ∥ ℓ ∞ (∂Q),which is (5.1).",
    "Given a cubeQ ⊂ R d and a function f: Q → R, we let f Q be the value of f at the center of the cube Q.",
    "For any cube Q ⊂ R d of side length r > 0 and any Lipschitz maps f, g: Q → R and π, κ: Q → R d it holds that Q f det Dπ - Q g det Dκ ≤ r d+1 (Lip(f) + Lip(g)) 1 2 √ dL d + r d |f Q -g Q |L d + r d-1 |f Q |c d L d-1 ∥π -κ∥ ℓ ∞ (∂Q), (5.3)where L is the maximum of the Lipschitz constants of the functions π 1,..., π d, κ 1,..., κ d. Before we continue with the proof of Lemma 5.2, since the estimate is quite technical, we first point out why it will later be useful.",
    "There are four summands on the right hand side of (5.3)."
